<div class="aos-EventTab main aos-FL100 active" data-tabid="1">
<div id="aos-EventLogo" class="aos-FL aos-W33 aos-PRM aos-Br2-W100-KP aos-Br2-P0">
<img loading="lazy" src="https&#x3a;&#x2f;&#x2f;drsw10gc90t0z.cloudfront.net&#x2f;AcuCustom&#x2f;Sitename&#x2f;DAM&#x2f;510&#x2f;ya-book-prize-2024-badge_8vo3iab4j97b.png" alt="The&#x20;YA&#x20;Book&#x20;Prize" title="The&#x20;YA&#x20;Book&#x20;Prize" class="aos-Image aos-MW100 aos-MBS aos-Br2-W25 aos-Br4-W50" />
</div>
<div id="aos-EventMainInfo" class="aos-FR aos-W66 aos-Br2-W100-KP aos-MB20px">
<div class="aos-FL100 aos-DS38-Intro aos-NL aos-MBS"><p>Weâre looking for the best YA novels from the UK and Ireland!</p>
<div style="display: grid; padding: 20px;"><img style="-webkit-filter: drop-shadow(5px 5px 5px #333); width: 55%; transform: rotate(10deg); margin: 0 auto;" src="https://www.thebookseller.com/AcuCustom/Sitename/DAM/487/whenourworldscollided_Main.gif"></div></div>
<div class="aos-FL100 aos-DS38-WYSEdit aos-MBM"> <p>The YA Book Prize launched in 2014 to celebrate great books for teenagers and young adults and aims to get more teens reading and buying books. It is the first prize in the UK and Ireland to specifically focus on fiction for young adults.</p>
<p class="elementToProof">Previous winners of the prize are Louise OâNeillâs <em>Only Ever Yours</em>Â (2015), Sarah Crossanâs <em>One </em>(2016), Patrice Lawrenceâs <em>Orangeboy</em>Â (2017), Will Hillâs <em>After the Fire</em>Â (2018), Sara Barnardâs <em>Goodbye, Perfect</em>Â (2019), Juno Dawsonâs <em>Meat Market </em>(2020), Alice Osemanâs <em>Loveless </em>(2021) and Adiba Jaigirdarâs<em>Â Hani and Ishuâs Guide to Fake Dating</em>Â (2022).Â </p>
<p class="elementToProof">Last yearâs prize went to <em>When Our Worlds Collided</em>Â by Danielle Jawando (published by Simon &amp; Schuster Childrenâs), a coming-of-age novel set in Moss Side, Manchester which follows three teenagers who must grapple with racialised injustice and institutional prejudice. Read Jawandoâs <a href="https://www.thebookseller.com/author-interviews/ya-book-prize-shortlist-danielle-jawando-in-conversation-about-when-our-worlds-collided">interview with The Bookseller</a>.</p>
<p>The prize is organised by book trade magazine The Bookseller and is run in partnership with Edinburgh International Book Festival. The shortlist is selected by a team at The Bookseller and the winner is selected by a panel of expert and teenage judges, who are asked to pick the book they believe is the best-written and that they would be most likely to share with young adults.</p> </div>
