<div id="ao-Step133" class="ao-Step50 aos-TAL aos-PRM">
<div class="aos-DS38-WYSEdit aos-MBM"> <h1><strong>2019</strong></h1><p>Â </p><p><strong>Sara Barnard</strong>Â won the YA Book Prize in its fifth year for her "unflinching" and âutterly rivetingâ contemporary novel about the impact of a teacher-student relationship,Â <strong><em>Goodbye, Perfect</em></strong><em>Â </em>(published by Macmillan Childrenâs Books).</p><p>The novel tells the story of Eden, who is forced to question everything when her steady, straight-A best friend Bonnie runs away with a teacher five days before the start of their GCSEs. Sworn to secrecy and bound by loyalty, only Eden knows Bonnieâs location, and sheâs forced to weigh up betraying her best friend with police questioning, suspicious parents and her own growing doubts.Â </p><p>Everyday Sexism founder and writer Laura Bates, who was one of the prize judges, said: "Sara Barnard's writing is an absolute triumph: this book is unputdownable and beautiful, unflinching in its exploration of important and complex topics from sexual exploitation to the foster care system. But it is also a joy to read, a tender portrayal of family and sibling relationships, of flawed and poignant female friendships and of the nuanced reality of teenage experiences and the journey to discovering who you are and what you stand for." Fellow judge andÂ author Alex Wheatle calledÂ <em>Goodbye, Perfect</em>Â âan utterly riveting readâ, adding âit wouldnât let me goâ.</p><p>The winner was selected from a shortlist that also included:Â <em>Clean</em>Â by Juno Dawson (published by Quercus Children's Books),Â <em>Big Bones</em>Â by Laura Dockrill (published by Hot Key Books),<em>Â I Am Thunder</em>Â by Muhammad Khan (published by Macmillan Childrenâs Books),Â <em>The Surface Breaks</em>Â by Louise O'Neill (published by Scholastic),Â <em>White Rabbit, Red Wolf</em>Â by Tom Pollock (published by Walker Books),Â <em>I Was Born for This</em>Â by Alice Oseman (published by HarperCollins Children's Books),Â <em>Outwalkers</em>Â by Fiona Shaw (published by David Fickling Books),Â <em>Only Love Can Break Your Heart</em>Â by Katherine Webber (published by Walker Books), andÂ <em>A Sky Painted Gold</em>Â by Laura Wood (published by Scholastic).</p> </div>
</div>
