<div id="ao-Step135" class="ao-Step50 aos-TAL aos-PRM">
<div class="aos-DS38-WYSEdit aos-MBM"> <h1><strong>2018</strong></h1><p>Â </p><p>In 2018, the YA Book Prize went toÂ <strong><em>Will HillÂ </em></strong>forÂ <strong><em>After the FireÂ </em></strong>(published by Usborne).</p><p><em>After the FireÂ </em>tells the story of teenage girl Moonbeam, who is trying to come to terms with her past and prepare for a new life after leaving behind the cult she grew up in.</p><p>Author Louise OâNeillâwinner of first ever YA Book Prize, and one of the 2018 judgesâsaid: "<em>After the Fire</em>Â is an engrossing, brilliantly realised story which is almost impossible to put down. Both thoughtfully structured and fast-paced, it is one of the most sensitive portrayals of trauma that I have read in a long time." Fellow judges Akala, a hip-hop artist, writer and historian, and blogger and YouTuber Lucy Powrie described it as a "well-written book on a challenging subject" and "a perfect showcase of what UK YA should be".</p><p>The judges selected the winning title from a shortlist that also included:Â <em>S.T.A.G.S.</em>Â by M A Bennett (published by Hot Key Books),Â <em>The One Memory of Flora Banks</em>Â by Emily Barr (published by Penguin),Â <em>It Only Happens in the Movies</em>Â by Holly Bourne (published by Usborne),Â <em>Moonrise</em>Â by Sarah Crossan (published by Bloomsbury),<em>Â Indigo Donut</em>Â by Patrice Lawrence (published by Hodder Childrenâs),Â <em>Release</em>Â by Patrick Ness (published by Walker Books),Â <em>Things a Bright Girl Can Do</em>Â by Sally Nicholls (published by Andersen Press),Â <em>La Belle Sauvage</em>Â by Philip Pullman (published by David Fickling Books/Penguin), andÂ <em>Straight Outta Crongton</em>Â by Alex Wheatle (published by Atom).</p><p>AÂ <strong>YA Book Prize Special Achievement Award</strong>Â was also given to Stripes Publishing and the authors of its YA anthologyÂ <em><strong>A Change is Gonna Come</strong></em>, to recognise their work in tackling the lack of diversity in YA publishing in the UK and Ireland.</p> </div>
