<div class="aos-DS38-WYSEdit aos-MBM"> <h1><strong>2017</strong></h1><p>Â </p><p>In 2017, the YA Book Prize went toÂ <strong><em>Orangeboy</em>Â by Patrice Lawrence</strong>Â (published by Hodder Childrenâs Books).</p><p><em>Orangeboy</em>Â tells the story of 16-year-old Marlon, who finds himself facing tough choices after a date ends in tragedy. Despite not wanting to follow his older brother Andre down the wrong path, Marlon gets caught up in Londonâs gang culture and things soon start to spiral out of control.</p><p>Author Melvin Burgess, one of the prize judges, said: â<em>Orangeboy</em>Â ticked so many boxes for so many of the judges. Itâs a page-turning thriller. The characters and their relationships are truthful, delightful, surprising and strong. It was so refreshing to read something set in an urban black community that will appeal to a diverse UK readership. It deals with family, friendship, sex appeal, loyalty and generally being human. It is so accomplished and we all really feel there is something there for everyone.â</p><p>The other shortlisted books, whittled down from more than 100 entries, were:Â <em>Beautiful Broken ThingsÂ </em>by Sara Barnard (published by Macmillan Childrenâs Books),<em>Â Chasing the Stars</em>Â by Malorie Blackman (published by Penguin Random House Childrenâs),<em>Â </em><em>The Graces</em>Â by Laure Eve (published by Faber Childrenâs),Â <em>How Not to Disappear</em>Â by Clare Furniss (published by Simon &amp; Schuster Childrenâs),Â <em>Paper ButterfliesÂ </em>by Lisa Heathfield (published by Egmont),Â <em>The Call</em>Â by Peadar OâGuilin (published by David Fickling Books),Â <em>The Monstrous Child</em>Â by Francesca Simon (published by Faber Childrenâs),Â <em>RiverkeepÂ </em>by Martin Stewart (published by Penguin Random House Childrenâs), andÂ <em>Crongton Knights</em>Â by Alex Wheatle (published by Atom).</p> </div>
