<div class="aos-DS38-WYSEdit aos-MBM"> <h1><strong>2016</strong></h1><p>Â </p><p>The YA Book Prize 2016 was won byÂ <strong>Sarah Crossan'sÂ <em>One</em>Â </strong>(published by Bloomsbury). One is about conjoined twins Grace and Tippi, who, after years of being educated at home, go to public school for the first time. Over the course of the novel the sisters make friends who have their own problems, whilst facing a serious medical choice.</p><p>The judges were unanimous in their decision thatÂ <em>One</em>Â should be this 2016âs winner.</p><p>Judge and writer Bim Adewunmi said she "fell in love" with the book.</p><p>"Tippi and Grace are a great addition to the pantheon of great literary sisters, and the way Crossan explores their rare (physical) bond only makes them more so," she said. "I cried on the train at the end and I will not soon forget either of these girls."</p><p>Sarah beat competition from nine other shortlisted books:Â <em>Am I Normal Yet?Â </em>by Holly Bourne (published by Usborne)<em>, Unbecoming</em>Â by Jenny Downham (published by David Fickling Books),Â <em>The Lie TreeÂ </em>by Frances Hardinge (published by Macmillan Childrenâs Books),Â <em>The Curious Tale of the Lady CarabooÂ </em>by Catherine Johnson<em>Â </em>(published by Penguin Random House Childrenâs),Â <em>The Rest of Us Just Live Here</em>Â by Patrick Ness (published by Walker Books),Â <em>Asking For ItÂ </em>by Louise OâNeill (published by Quercus),Â <em>The Sin Eaterâs Daughter</em>Â by Melinda Salisbury (published by Scholastic),Â <em>Concentr8Â </em>by William Sutcliffe (published by Bloomsbury), andÂ <em>The Art of Being Normal</em>Â by Lisa Williamson (published by David Fickling Books).</p><p>Â </p><p>AÂ <strong>YA Book Prize Special Achievement Award</strong>Â went toÂ <a href="https://www.thebookseller.com/news/burgess-junk-earns-author-ya-award-327563" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Melvin Burgess</strong></a>, whose novelÂ <em>Junk</em>, one of the first Y